  "narrative": {
    "intro": "Federal contracting in Texas reached $69.1B in obligations for FY2026 to date, with 142,957 awards and an average award size of $483K; obligations are down 20.0% year over year. The fiscal series shows variation across recent years, with FY21 at $55.1B, FY22 at $67.6B, FY23 at $81.9B, FY24 at $59.3B, and FY25 at $86.3B before the current FY26 total of $69.1B. The Department of Defense leads buying in the state with $27.7B in obligations, followed by the Department of Homeland Security with $21.9B and the Department of Veterans Affairs with $14.7B. Top vendors include LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $10B and MCKESSON CORPORATION at $9.7B, with additional large awards to LOCKHEED MARTIN CORPORATION at $6.1B and others. Construction and manufacturing sectors account for large shares of obligations, led by Commercial and Institutional Building Construction at $17.5B, Pharmaceutical Preparation Manufacturing at $9.8B, and Guided Missile and Space Vehicle Manufacturing at $9.7B. The current-year totals are partial (fiscal year to date).",
    "sections": [
